    <text>
        <front/>
        <body>
            <pb n="2" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#i">HUMBOLDT ON EMIGRATION TO<lb break="yes"/>CENTRAL AMERICA.</hi>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <milestone unit="section" rendition="#hr"/>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                </head>
                <p>
                    <hi rendition="#c">TO JOHN CARMICHAEL, ESQ., LIVERPOOL.</hi>
                </p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>
                    <hi rendition="#et">Dec. 1, 1850.</hi>
                </p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>Dear Sir&#x2014;Trusting that the accompanying translation<lb break="yes"/>of a letter from Alexander Von Humboldt to our society may<lb break="yes"/>be interesting to you, as tending to show the desire felt for<lb break="yes"/>its success in a high quarter, I take the liberty of forwarding<lb break="yes"/>the same to you, and to assure you of the respect with<lb break="yes"/>which <hi rendition="#et">I remain, dear Sir,<lb break="yes"/>Yours most obediently,<lb break="yes"/>(Signed) <hi rendition="#k">Bulow.</hi>
                    </hi>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <milestone unit="section" rendition="#hr"/>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <hi rendition="#c">(Translation.)</hi>
                </p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <div n="2">
                    <head>TO THE MEMBERS OF THE PROVISIONAL COMMITTEE OF<lb break="yes"/>THE BERLIN COLONISATION SOCIETY FOR CENTRAL<lb break="yes"/>AMERICA.</head>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <dateline>
                        <hi rendition="#et">Potsdam, Nov. 7, 1850.</hi>
                    </dateline>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <p>I return my respectful and sincere thanks to the distin-<lb break="no" />guished men forming the Committee of the B.C.S. for<lb break="yes" />Central America for their obliging letter of the 30th of<lb break="yes" />October.</p>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <p>Their comprehensive views on the subject of an enlarged<lb break="yes" />intercourse with different parts of the globe, and their salu-<lb break="no"/>tary aid in directing the course of German emigration, call<lb break="yes"/>forth my warmest approbation. However unsettled the<lb break="yes"/>political state of the country may be, yet I do not doubt<lb break="yes"/>that his Majesty the King will encourage such a patriotic<lb break="yes"/>and useful undertaking, the principles of which (strength-<lb break="no"/>ened as they are by my own experience) I shall always be<lb break="yes"/>happy to advocate to the best of my ability. The under-<lb break="no"/>taking has already been productive of benefit, as it has given<lb break="yes"/>rise to interesting investigations into the conformation, the<lb break="yes"/>climate, and the natural productions of a beautiful part of<lb break="yes"/>the tropical regions.</p>
                    <lb break="yes"/>
                    <closer>
                        <salute>
                            <hi rendition="#et">With every mark of the highest respect,<lb break="yes"/>I have the honour to be, Gentlemen,<lb break="yes" />Your most obedient servant,<lb break="yes"/>(Signed) <hi rendition="#k">Alexander von Humboldt.</hi>
                                <lb break="yes"/>
                                <milestone unit="section" rendition="#hr"/>
                                <lb break="yes"/>
                            </hi>
                        </salute>
                    </closer>
                </div>
            </div>
